entry.content:
Two autorollers (maybe more) do not send out notifications to the waterfall gardener on stuck rolls anymore.
@szuend mentioned that the waterfall gardener's mail was changed for skia autorollers, maybe that has messed up something?
1. "Update Chrome (for Testing) PIN" 2. "Update devtools-frontend (trusted)"

# Steps to reproduce the problem
This is regression from chromium 121.0.6167.160-1~deb12u1 to chromium 122.0.6261.94-1~deb12u1 .

Create manifest v2 extension (sources of the extension below). Install the extension.

Then compile C++ program below.

Properly configure browser for native messaging as described in https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/develop/concepts/native-messaging#native-messaging-host in section "Native messaging host" (my config for native messaging is below).

Then click at extension icon multiple times.

Extension sources:
manifest.json:

********
{
  "name": "a",
  "version": "0.1",
  "description": "a",
  "manifest_version": 2,

  "permissions": [
    "<all_urls>",
    "nativeMessaging"
  ],

  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"],
    "persistent": false
  },

  "browser_action": {}
}
********

background.js:
********
"use strict";

chrome.browserAction.onClicked.addListener(() => {
  const port = chrome.runtime.connectNative("foo");
  port.onMessage.addListener(() => alert("got message"));
  port.postMessage({})
});
********

Config for native messaging foo.json:
********
{
  "name": "foo",
  "description": "foo",
  "path": "/home/user/foo",
  "type": "stdio",
  "allowed_origins": [
    "chrome-extension://dfhpcmjdgjeobmipgaibgpakcjmcmijg/"
  ]
}
********

C++ program:
********
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdint.h>

#include <string>

int
main (void)
{
  uint32_t size_of_input;
  if (fread(&size_of_input, sizeof size_of_input, 1, stdin) != 1)
    {
      abort ();
    }
  char *input = new char[size_of_input];
  if (fread(input, size_of_input, 1, stdin) != 1)
    {
      abort ();
    }
  delete [] input;
  std::string output = "{\"data\":[";
  for (int i = 0; i != 10000; ++i)
    {
      output += "10,";
    }
  output += "10]}";
  uint32_t size_of_output = output.size();
  if (fwrite(&size_of_output, sizeof size_of_output, 1, stdout) != 1)
    {
      abort ();
    }
  if (fwrite(output.data(), output.size(), 1, stdout) != 1)
    {
      abort ();
    }
  return 0;
}
********

# Problem Description
Alert "got message" should appear, but it usually doesn't. In my tests it never appears. Even if it somehow appear, try again several times. Even if it appears, it appears unreliable. This happens with chromium 122.

There is no such bug in chromium 121. "got message" always reliable appears

# Additional Comments
My OS is debian linux bookworm x86_64. I installed chromium from debian

# Summary
Regression 121->122. Native messaging in manif v2 ext is unreliable if native app sends 30 000 bytes

